##Chapter 2: The Two Rhythms of the Universe: Looping and Non-Looping
When we observe the universe, we notice that everything seems to have a rhythm: planets orbit, the moon waxes and wanes, tides rise and fall, life is born and dies… These events look like parts of a giant cosmic symphony.

We can divide these rhythms into two main types. Looping means events or states repeat in a pattern — either exactly or in a spiral-like evolution. Non-looping means events seem to happen only once, or appear still, with no clear cycle.

But does true "non-looping" actually exist? Or is it just a limitation of how we perceive and understand time and motion?



2.1　A World of Loops: The Visible and the Hidden Rhythms
The most familiar loops come from nature and life itself: the changing of day and night and the four seasons, the moon's cycle pulling the tides, the heartbeat and breath that keep us alive, the cycle of birth, aging, and death, and the movement of water and elements through ecosystems.

These repeating events give us the sense that the universe has a circular nature, echoing Laozi's words: "Reversal is the movement of the Dao." Everything reaches an extreme, then reverses — the sun rises high, then begins to set; greatness fades.

But beyond these obvious loops, there are deeper and slower rhythms in the universe. They may be too slow for us to notice, or exist in forms we aren't used to recognizing.



2.2　Stillness or Another Kind of Repetition?
Traditionally, we think of "stillness" as meaning "nothing happening" or "the end.”

But in Non-Infinity Theory, stillness is not emptiness — it's a form of repeated state. Even a moment of "nothing" must have a start of the stillness, a continuation of that stillness, and finally an end of the stillness. So even "nothing" becomes a loop of stillness. There is no true "unchanging nothingness" — only different ways that "nothing" repeats over time.

Let's look at some examples of things that seem non-looping: a cup of water sitting on a table, a person standing still, a frozen lake. At first, they seem like "nothing is happening.”

But look closer. Water molecules are still vibrating at a microscopic level. Your body is working — organs function, cells change, electric signals fire. Beneath the frozen lake, small shifts still occur and ice crystals are slowly moving.

Even if something looks still to our eyes, it may simply be a repetition of the same state. If we take one picture every second of a frozen lake and each picture looks almost the same, this "almost-unchanging" repetition becomes what we call stillness.

So here is a new idea: stillness is a loop too — just a slow, subtle one. Not as loud as a heartbeat or as obvious as the seasons, but it is still a pattern repeating over time.



2.3　A Still Stone, A Moving Universe: Seeing Beyond the Senses
To our senses, a stone seems perfectly still. It doesn't move. It doesn't grow. It feels cold and lifeless. But science and the universe tell us something very different.


In the micro world, stones are always moving.
In quantum physics, even if you cool a stone near absolute zero (–273.15°C), its particles still hold a tiny amount of energy. This is called zero-point energy. Electrons don't sit still — they exist in shifting clouds around the nucleus. Molecules tremble due to heat and quantum movement. There is no true stillness in the universe. All matter moves, at least on the atomic level.


From a larger scale, even a stone on the ground is flying through space.
Earth spins at about 1,670 km/h. Earth orbits the sun at 107,000 km/h. Our solar system moves through the galaxy at 230 km per second. The galaxy itself is moving through space. That still stone is speeding through the universe with you — but because you're moving too, at the same speed, you don't feel it. So is stillness just an illusion? From a cosmic view, everything is part of endless motion.


A stone also has a long journey through time.
Maybe it came from a volcano. Maybe it rolled down a river thousands of years ago. Someday it may crack, be picked up, or slowly break into soil. That "still" stone is just pausing briefly in a much bigger cycle. Even a single second isn't truly frozen — if we zoom in far enough, things are always moving.


Even when you sit quietly, you are not truly still.
Your thoughts keep moving. Your emotions shift. Your cells are changing. Your brain waves are active. Your heart keeps its rhythm. What looks like human stillness is actually a kind of inner motion — another form of a loop, just happening on the inside.



2.4　The Repetition of Stillness: The "Nothing" and "Something" of the Universe
In Non-Infinity Theory, stillness has three stages: something starts to be still, that stillness is maintained, and then that stillness is finally broken. So "nothing" is not truly eternal — it's just a loop of stillness. Even when nothing is happening, it's still "something" — it's the state of nothing happening, repeating.


A dog's quiet moment
Imagine a dog running after a ball. Clearly, it's moving. Now imagine the dog sitting still, doing nothing. But is it really doing nothing? It's actually repeating a still pose — muscles stay tense, eyes stay focused, heart beats, breath flows. It's "doing nothing" again and again, until it moves. That's a loop of stillness.


Before the Universe: Did Stillness Come First?
Let's ask a big question: what was there before the universe existed?

Science says: "Nothing." But that doesn't fully answer the puzzle. How did something come out of nothing?

Maybe before the Big Bang, the universe was in a perfect still loop — a long, quiet repetition of "nothing happening." Like the quiet dog sitting still, like the frozen lake, this state kept repeating the same emptiness, over and over. Nothing was being created. Nothing was changing. But that repetition itself was a cycle — a loop of nothing.

Then one day — boom. The stillness broke. The loop ended. The universe began. Time, space, energy, matter — all started moving.

So maybe the universe did not come from "pure nothing." It came from a loop of stillness that was finally interrupted.

Imagine an empty room with no sound, no light, no movement. But the fact that the room "is empty" — doesn't that fact keep repeating itself, second by second? That quiet repetition of emptiness is its own kind of loop. Non-Infinity Theory suggests: the universe didn't start from nothing — it woke up from a very long, very quiet loop.



2.5　The Beginning and End of “Nothingness"

The Start of Nothingness
If "nothingness" existed before the Big Bang, then logically it must have had a start. If it never started, how could the Big Bang ever happen out of it? That would be a break in logic.

Any state — even total emptiness — must begin somewhere. This "nothing" wasn't a timeless vacuum outside the universe. It was more likely a special still state before one phase of the universe turned into another.

If "nothing" were truly absolute and eternal, then there could never be a start, end, or any chance of change. True eternal nothing could never give rise to "something." But we do exist. The universe happened. Life and galaxies came to be. Our very existence proves that "nothingness" did not last forever.


The End of Nothingness
If that still loop of nothing had a start, it must also have an end. No loop is truly infinite — not even the loop of perfect stillness.

The Big Bang did not come out of a complete void. It came from the breaking of a still loop — like a frozen lake that suddenly cracks after a long winter, or a light bulb in total darkness that suddenly shines when power returns.

The universe didn't appear out of nowhere. It woke up from an extreme loop of stillness. It wasn't "something from nothing" — it was a new cycle born from an old one.



2.6　The Law of Large Numbers and Why the Universe Had to Appear
Imagine flipping a fair coin. Each toss is independent — the coin has no memory and doesn't try to correct any imbalance. But when we expand the number of tosses to hundreds of thousands, a surprising pattern appears: heads and tails tend to come out in nearly equal amounts. This is called the Law of Large Numbers.

This hides a deep idea: every single event is random and independent, but together, they form a highly ordered pattern. The randomness of the individual and the certainty of the group seem to clash — but they work together.


Something Had to Happen
Even if a cycle has a 99.99% chance of continuing and only a 0.01% chance of ending, given enough time, the end will inevitably come. Just like flipping a coin — with enough tosses, both heads and tails must eventually appear. No matter how small the chance, given enough time, the rare becomes the inevitable.

Non-looping is itself a kind of loop: it has a start, enters a cycle of "nothing happening," and eventually reaches an end. Inside this loop of emptiness, two possibilities are quietly waiting: continue the loop of emptiness, or end the emptiness and move toward change. Even if the first option has a 99.99999% chance of happening, with enough cycles, the second option will eventually appear.




So the end of nothingness was not an accident — the appearance of the universe was inevitable. As long as any mechanism of choice exists, even one strongly biased toward stillness, change will eventually come.
Before we move on, take a moment to think: the "stillness" you know — is it truly empty, or is it a loop you just haven't seen yet?
